# This colorize_mask class takes in a numpy segmentation mask,
#  and then converts it to a PIL Image for visualization.
#  Since by default the numpy matrix contains integers from
#  0,1,...,num_classes, we need to apply some color to this
#  so we can visualize easier! Refer to:
#  https://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/4.1.x/reference/Image.html#PIL.Image.Image.putpalette
palette = [0, 0, 0, 128, 0, 0, 0, 128, 0, 128, 128, 0, 0, 0, 128, 128, 0, 128, 0, 128, 128,
           128, 128, 128, 64, 0, 0, 192, 0, 0, 64, 128, 0, 192, 128, 0, 64, 0, 128, 192, 0, 128,
           64, 128, 128, 192, 128, 128, 0, 64, 0, 128, 64, 0, 0, 192, 0, 128, 192, 0, 0, 64, 128]

def colorize_mask(mask):
    new_mask = Image.fromarray(mask.astype(np.uint8)).convert('P')
    new_mask.putpalette(palette)

    return new_mask

def add_img_plot(fig, index, img, title, sub_plot_id):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(sub_plot_id[0],sub_plot_id[1],sub_plot_id[2])
    plt.title(title + str(index))
    ax.imshow(img)

Problem 1 Data Augmentation¶

The transform below is used to create a transformed training dataset. It currently center crops all images.

Modify it so that:

  • There is a 50% chance the images will be flipped horizontally
  • Instead of a center crop, a random part of the image is cropped

Useful functions:

  • chainercv.transforms.flip
  • chainercv.transforms.random_crop

Note: The output image and segmented images should match

In [5]:
# From ImageNet dataset
norm = ([0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
        [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])

def tensor_to_img(tensor):
    # Denormalize tensor and convert to uint8 np array for visualization
    denormalize = transforms.Normalize(
        mean=[-m / s for m, s in zip(norm[0], norm[1])],
        std=[1.0 / s for s in norm[1]]
    )
    np_img = np.moveaxis((denormalize(tensor).numpy() * 255), -3, -1).astype(np.uint8)

    return np_img

# Modify this function
def voc_train_transform(in_data):
    size = (110,110)
    img, seg_img = in_data

    # Add channel to seg img
    seg_img = seg_img[None]

    # TODO: 50% chance of flipping the image horizontally
    if random.random() > 0.5:
        img = chainercv.transforms.flip(img, x_flip=True)
        seg_img = chainercv.transforms.flip(seg_img, x_flip=True)

    # TODO: Since random crop_can't handle multiple inputs, combine the images so they can be cropped with the same randomization
    # First, determine the coordinates for cropping the image
    # Then apply the same crop dimensions to both img and seg_img
    img, crop_params = chainercv.transforms.random_crop(img, size, return_param=True)
    seg_img = seg_img[:, crop_params['y_slice'], crop_params['x_slice']][0]

    # Convert input img to tensor and normalize
    img = np.rollaxis(img, 0, 3)
    img = transforms.ToPILImage()(np.uint8(img))
    img = transforms.ToTensor()(img)
    img = transforms.Normalize(norm[0],norm[1])(img)

    return img, torch.from_numpy(seg_img.copy()).long()

img_119, seg_img_119 = voc_train_transform(voc_train_data[119])
img_273, seg_img_273 = voc_train_transform(voc_train_data[273])
img_225, seg_img_225 = voc_train_transform(voc_train_data[225])

# Create the figure size
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
# Car image 119
add_img_plot(fig, 119, tensor_to_img(img_119), 'Image ', [3,2,1])
add_img_plot(fig, 119, colorize_mask(seg_img_119.numpy()), 'Segmented Image ', [3,2,2])
# Car image 273
add_img_plot(fig, 273, tensor_to_img(img_273), 'Image ', [3,2,3])
add_img_plot(fig, 273, colorize_mask(seg_img_273.numpy()), 'Segmented Image ', [3,2,4])
# Bicycle image 225

from torchvision.models import ResNet34_Weights

class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes):
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes

        # Keep the dropout rate relatively low
        # self.dropout1 = nn.Dropout(p=0.3)
        # self.dropout2 = nn.Dropout(p=0.2)
        # self.dropout3 = nn.Dropout(p=0.2)
        # self.dropout4 = nn.Dropout(p=0.1)
        # self.dropout5 = nn.Dropout(p=0.1)

        self.bn1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(num_features=256)
        self.bn2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(num_features=128)
        # self.bn3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(num_features=64)
        # self.bn4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(num_features=64)

        # Maintain 'same' padding to make sure concatenated images have the same size
        # The number of channels should mirror the encoder
        # self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=768, out_channels=256, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=640, out_channels=128, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        # self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=192, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        # self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.conv5 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=num_classes, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')

        # Use the most recent ResNet34 weights
        self.resnet = models.resnet34(pretrained=True)

        # Freeze all pre-trained parameters except layer 4, which we'll fine-tune
        for param in self.resnet.parameters():
            param.requires_grad = False
        for param in self.resnet.layer4.parameters():
            param.requires_grad = True

    def forward(self, inp):
        # Fill in model to produce lfinal

        # Store the initial size for upsampling
        h0, w0 = inp.size(2), inp.size(3)   # torch.Size([1, 3, 110, 110])

        # Layer 0
        x0 = self.resnet.conv1(inp)         # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        x0 = self.resnet.bn1(x0)            # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        x0 = self.resnet.relu(x0)           # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        # x0 = self.dropout1(x0)               # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])

        # Layer 1
        x1 = self.resnet.maxpool(x0)        # torch.Size([1, 64, 28, 28])
        x1 = self.resnet.layer1(x1)         # torch.Size([1, 64, 28, 28])

        # Layer 2
        x2 = self.resnet.layer2(x1)         # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])

        # Layer 3
        x3 = self.resnet.layer3(x2)         # torch.Size([1, 256, 7, 7])

        # Layer 4
        x = self.resnet.layer4(x3)          # torch.Size([1, 512, 4, 4])

        # Upsampling 1
        # x = F.interpolate(x, size=(x3.size(2), x3.size(3)))   # torch.Size([1, 512, 7, 7])
        # x = torch.cat((x, x3), dim=1)       # torch.Size([1, 768, 7, 7])
        # x = self.conv1(x)                   # torch.Size([1, 256, 7, 7])
        # x = self.bn1(x)                     # torch.Size([1, 256, 7, 7])
        # x = nn.ReLU()(x)                    # torch.Size([1, 256, 7, 7])
        # x = self.dropout2(x)                # torch.Size([1, 256, 7, 7])

        # Upsampling 2
        x = F.interpolate(x, size=(x2.size(2), x2.size(3))) # torch.Size([1, 256, 14, 14])
        x = torch.cat((x, x2), dim=1)       # torch.Size([1, 384, 14, 14])
        x = self.conv2(x)                   # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])
        x = self.bn2(x)                     # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])
        x = nn.ReLU()(x)                    # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])
        # x = self.dropout3(x)                # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])

        # Upsampling 3
        # x = F.interpolate(x, size=(x1.size(2), x1.size(3))) # torch.Size([1, 128, 28, 28])
        # x = torch.cat((x, x1), dim=1)       # torch.Size([1, 192, 28, 28])
        # x = self.conv3(x)                   # torch.Size([1, 64, 28, 28])
        # x = self.bn3(x)                     # torch.Size([1, 64, 28, 28])
        # x = nn.ReLU()(x)                    # torch.Size([1, 64, 28, 28])
        # x = self.dropout4(x)                # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])

        # Upsampling 4
        # x = F.interpolate(x, size=(x0.size(2), x0.size(3))) # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        # x = torch.cat((x, x0), dim=1)       # torch.Size([1, 128, 55, 55])
        # x = self.conv4(x)                   # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        # x = self.bn4(x)                     # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        # x = nn.ReLU()(x)                    # torch.Size([1, 64, 55, 55])
        # x = self.dropout5(x)                # torch.Size([1, 128, 14, 14])

        # Upsampling 5
        x = F.interpolate(x, size=(inp.size(2), inp.size(3)))   # torch.Size([1, 64, 110, 110])
        # x = torch.cat((x, inp), dim=1)          # torch.Size([1, 67, 110, 110])
        x = self.conv5(x)                       # torch.Size([1, 21, 110, 110])

        # Return the final prediction
        return x

def train(train_loader, net, criterion, optimizer, loss_graph, device):

    for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(train_loader):
        img, gt_seg_img = data.to(device), target.to(device)

        # This is a forward pass which also returns loss due to training mode
        output = net(img)
        loss = criterion(output, gt_seg_img)

        # Populate this list to graph the loss
        loss_graph.append(loss.item())

        # View the loss within the epoch
        print(loss.item())

        # Zero gradients, perform a backward pass, and update the weights.
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

    return loss

    ax.clear()

    ax.plot(loss_graph, label='training loss')
    ax.legend(loc='upper right')
    fig.canvas.draw()
    print("Epoch: {} Loss: {}".format(e, loss))

def validate(val_loader, net):
    iou_arr = []

    net.eval()

    with torch.no_grad():
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(val_loader):
            img, gt_seg_img = data.to(device), target.to(device)

            output = net(img)

            # Convert to numpy arrays
            if device != 'cpu':
                output = output.cpu()
                gt_seg_img = gt_seg_img.cpu()
            pred = torch.argmax(output, dim=1).numpy()[0]

            gt_np = gt_seg_img.numpy()[0]

            conf = eval_semantic_segmentation(pred[None], gt_np[None])

            iou_arr.append(conf['miou'])

    return sum(iou_arr) / len(iou_arr)

# a validation loader is created with a transform that doesn't modify the data
voc_val_data = VOCSemanticSegmentationDataset(data_dir=DATASET_LOCATION + 'VOC2012', split='val')

def val_transform(in_data):
    img, seg_img = in_data

    img = np.rollaxis(img, 0, 3)
    img = transforms.ToPILImage()(np.uint8(img))
    img = transforms.ToTensor()(img)
    img = transforms.Normalize(mean=norm[0],std=norm[1])(img)

    return img, torch.from_numpy(seg_img.copy()).long()

voc_val_data_transformed = TransformDataset(voc_val_data, val_transform)

def add_img_txt_plot(fig, index, img, title, sub_plot_id, txt):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(sub_plot_id[0],sub_plot_id[1],sub_plot_id[2])

def get_nn_seg_img(net, data):
    img, gt_seg_img = data

    nn_seg_output = net.forward(img[None].cuda())

    # computing mIOU (quantitative measure of accuracy for network predictions)
    if device != 'cpu':
        nn_seg_img = torch.argmax(nn_seg_output, dim=1).cpu().numpy()[0]
    else:
        nn_seg_img = torch.argmax(nn_seg_output, dim=1).numpy()[0]

    gts = gt_seg_img.cpu().numpy()

    conf = eval_semantic_segmentation(nn_seg_img[None], gts[None])

    print("View count of pixels within each label category:")
    print(np.unique(gt_seg_img, return_counts=True))
    print(np.unique(nn_seg_img, return_counts=True))

    return nn_seg_img, conf['miou']
